                <li><strong>Day 14:</strong> Final follow-up: "I understand you're busy! My deadline is approaching‚Äîis this something you're able to support? If not, no worries, and I'd still love to explore partnership for future iterations."</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>WHAT TO SAY WHEN YOU MEET IN PERSON</h3>
            <p><strong>Script for Initial Conversation:</strong></p>
            <p style="font-style: italic; background: #f0f0f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">"Hi, I'm [Name]! Thanks for taking time to meet. I'm a queer artist from Nanaimo working on a fantasy project featuring a non-binary protagonist, and I'm applying for a Canada Council grant to fund it. I'm reaching out because [Organization Name] does such important work with [specific program/mission], and I'd love to partner with you‚Äînot just for the grant application, but because I want this project to actually serve your community members. Can I tell you a bit about the story and what partnership would look like?"</p>

            <p><strong>Key Points to Hit:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>YOU'RE LOCAL (especially for Generation Q) - this isn't some outsider extracting stories</li>
                <li>PAID PARTICIPATION - youth/community members get $200 each, this isn't free labor</li>
                <li>THEY HAVE CONTROL - if feedback says "this doesn't work," you'll change it</li>
                <li>LONG-TERM BENEFIT - 5% of revenue forever, not just one-time</li>
                <li>NO PRESSURE - if they can't do the letter right now, you'd still love to partner later</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>WHAT TO DO IF THEY'RE HESITANT</h3>
            <p><strong>Common Concerns & How to Address:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>"We're too busy right now"</strong> ‚Üí "Totally understand! Would writing 2-3 paragraphs be more manageable than a full letter? I can provide bullet points of what to include."</li>
                <li><strong>"We don't know you/your work"</strong> ‚Üí "That's fair! Can I show you my preliminary sketches and talk through the story? I'm also happy to connect you with [anyone you know in common or other org you've contacted]."</li>
                <li><strong>"We're not sure about the blockchain stuff"</strong> ‚Üí "I get it‚Äîcrypto has bad reputation. This is about making digital ownership accessible, not speculation. Happy to explain more, or we can focus the letter on the representation/community engagement parts."</li>
                <li><strong>"What if the grant doesn't come through?"</strong> ‚Üí "Great question! I'm committed to this project either way. If this grant doesn't work out, I'll apply for others or do a Kickstarter. Your letter isn't wasted even if this specific application doesn't succeed."</li>
                <li><strong>"We need to run this by our board/director"</strong> ‚Üí "Absolutely! How long does that usually take? Can I provide any additional materials to help them decide?"</li>
            </ul>
