            <p>My name is <span class="placeholder">[Your Name]</span>, and I'm a queer artist and storyteller right here in Nanaimo. I'm writing to request Generation Q's partnership on <strong>Spectral Quest: Rainbow Craft</strong>, a fantasy transmedia project I'm creating specifically for young 2SLGBTQI+ people like those in your program who deserve to see themselves as heroes in the stories they love. I'm applying for a Canada Council for the Arts grant to fund this work, and having Generation Q's support would be invaluable‚Äînot just for the grant application, but for ensuring this project actually serves our local queer youth.</p>

            <p><strong>What Is Spectral Quest?</strong> It's a complete fantasy universe featuring Lirien, a 20-year-old non-binary unicorn who uses they/them pronouns and has rainbow-weaving magic. The project includes an interactive browser game (seven levels you can play for free), an original fantasy novel, visual art, and even plans for stuffies and action figures. The story follows Lirien's quest to save their cousin Maxim (who was forcibly transformed into a cyborg by an authoritarian villain who hates anything that doesn't fit into neat binary categories) while restoring seven rainbow layers to a wounded world. It's about chosen family, healing from trauma, and the idea that being queer isn't something to "fix"‚Äîit's power.</p>

            <p><strong>Why This Matters for Generation Q Youth:</strong> When I talk to young queer people‚Äîwhether at Pride events, online, or through connections with Island organizations‚Äîthe feedback is always the same: "We're tired of being the tragic side character. We want to be the hero." Right now, only 2% of video games have LGBTQ+ main characters (according to GLAAD), and when queer characters do show up, they're often minor NPCs or their whole story is about suffering. Spectral Quest flips this: Lirien is powerful, their queerness is magic, and while the story acknowledges pain (the villain literally trying to erase color/diversity), it's fundamentally about joy and hope.</p>

            <p>For Nanaimo youth specifically‚Äîwho often feel isolated from Vancouver's bigger queer community‚Äîthis project says "Your stories matter. A queer person from YOUR city is creating fantasy worlds where you belong." That local connection is huge.</p>

